Project Final Submission¶

Step 1a: Planning¶

Identify the information in the file your program will read¶

Describe (all) the information that is available. Be sure to note any surprising or unusual features. (For example, some information sources have missing data, which may be blank or flagged using values like -99, NaN, or something else.)

The available information includes:
  • property information: including id, which is the unique integer that identities each airbnb property in the area. As well as property type and room type.
  • location of the property: including neighbourhood, which is the neighbourhood name where the property is located. As well as city, state, zipcode, and country.
  • accommodates: is an integer representing the maximum number of guests each property can accommodate per night. It is ranging from 1 to 20 inclusively.
  • price: the total price per night of the property. The price is an integer ranging from 0 to 10000 inclusively.
  • review scores rating: the overall guest review score for each Netherland Airbnb property. Review scores represent the overall rate of satisfaction of guests regarding the Airbnb properties (the higher the better). The scores are integers ranging from 0 to 100 inclusive.
  • review scores location: the guest review score for each Netherland Airbnb property. Review scores represent the rate of satisfaction of guests regarding the Airbnb properties’ location (the higher the score means the location of the property is more convenient). The scores are integers ranging from 0 to 10 inclusively.

  • neighbourhood_cleansed (10th column, which is index 9)

@typecheck
def read(filename: str) -> List[AirbnbProperty]:
    """    
    reads information from the specified file and returns a list of AirbnbProperty data, 
    there is no empty rows, and the data is valid, so we return all rows
    """
    # return []  #stub
    # Template from HtDAP
    
    # loap contains the result so far
    loap = [] # type: List[AirbnbProperty]

    with open(filename) as csvfile:
        
        reader = csv.reader(csvfile)
        next(reader) # skip header line

        for row in reader:
            # you may not need to store all the rows, and you may need
            # to convert some of the strings to other types
            
            # row[8] -> id of the property, will be parsed to int
            # row[9] -> neighbourhood of the property, will be parsed to neighbourhood
            # row[19] -> number of guests the property can accommodate, will be parsed to int
            # row[24] -> price of the property, will be parsed to int
            
            ap = AirbnbProperty(parse_int(row[8]),             # represents an int[0, ...), "id"
                                parse_neighbourhood (row[9]),  # represents neighbourhood
                                parse_int(row[19]),            # represents an int[1, 20], "guest_num"
                                parse_int(row[24]))            # represents an int[1, 10000], "price"                           
            loap.append(ap)
    return loap

@typecheck
def get_price_per_guest_by_neighbourhood(loap: List[AirbnbProperty]) -> List[float]: 
    
    """
    returns the list of price per guest of the given loap
    """
    # return [] # stub
    # template based on List[AirbnbProperty] and reference rule 
    # Airbnb Property seen in the list so far
    ap_seen = [] # type: List[float]
    
    for ap in loap: 
        ap_seen.append(calculate_price_per_guest(ap))
            
    return ap_seen

@typecheck
def calculate_price_per_guest(ap: AirbnbProperty) -> float: 
    """
    given an airbnbproperty, returns the average price per guest for each night of this airbnbproperty,
    calculated as dividing the price per night by the guest number
    """
    # return 0.0 # stub
    # template based on AirbnbProperty template
    return ap.price / ap.guest_num

@typecheck
def calculate_avg(lof: List[float]) -> float: 
    """
    returns the average of given list of float
    """
    # return 0.0 # stub
    # Template from List[float] 
    # price added so far
    sum_price = 0.0 # type: float
    
    for n in lof:
        sum_price = sum_price + n

    return sum_price / len(lof)

@typecheck
def list_all_avg (los:List[str], filename: str) -> List[float]:
    """
    takes a list of string of neighbourhood names 
    and returns the list of floats of the average prices
    """
    # return [] #stub
    # Template from List[str]
    # str seen in the list so far
    acc =[] # type: List[float]
    
    for s in los:
        acc.append (calculate_avg(get_price_per_guest_by_neighbourhood(filter_neighbourhood((read(filename)), s))))
    
    return acc

@typecheck
def display__charts(means_price: List[float],
                    neighbourhoods: List[str]) -> None:
    """
    takes the list of means of price and list of neighbourhood names
    and return the bar chart of the average price per guest for the neighbouhoods
    with the title of Average Prices per Guest of All Neighbourhoods in Neitherland
    """
    # return None  #stub
    # Template based on visualization
    
    # the width of each bar
    bar_width = 0.3

    
    # the middle coordinate for each of the bars for the first bar chart (treatment groups)
    middle_of_bars_price = produce_num_sequence(means_price, bar_width, 0.4)
    
    
    # the opacity for the bars. It must be between 0 and 1, and higher numbers are more
    # opaque (darker)
    opacity = 0.4
    
    # create the first bar chart
    rects1 = plt.bar(middle_of_bars_price, 
                     means_price,                # list containing the height for each bar, here the means
                     bar_width,
                     alpha=opacity,                  # set the opacity
                     align='edge',
                     color='b',                      # set the colour (here, blue)
                     label='price')


    # set the labels for the x-axis, y-axis, and plot title
    plt.xlabel('neighbourhood')
    plt.ylabel('average price per guest per night')
    plt.title('Average Prices per Guest of All Neighbourhoods in Neitherland')
    
    # set the x-coordinate for positioning the labels. Here, we want each label to be in the middle of each bar
    x_coord_labels = middle_of_bars_price
    
    # set x label orientation
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    
    #label = get_neighbourhood_labels(loap)
    
    plt.xticks(middle_of_bars_price, neighbourhoods)
    
    # show the plot
    plt.show()
    
    return None


@typecheck
def produce_num_sequence(values: List[float], initial: float, gap: float) -> List[float]:
    """
    Produce a list of numbers like [initial, initial + gap, initial + 2*gap, ...] of the same
    length as values, e.g., to give alignment coordinates for a plot. The number
    of numbers in the list is equal to len(values). The first value is initial. The gap between values
    is gap.
    
    E.g., [5,15,25,35,45,55,65,75] for 8 values, initial == 5, and gap == 10.
    """
    # return []  #stub
    # Template from List[float] with two additional parameters
    
    # nums is the numbers for the values seen so far
    nums = []  # type: List[int]
    
    # next_num is the next number to use
    next_num = initial
    
    for val in values:
        nums.append(next_num)
        next_num = next_num + gap
    
    return nums
